          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>What primarily regulates the body's switching between carbohydrate, lipid, and protein as fuel sources during fed and fasting states?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Plasma osmolality</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Osmolality governs water balance, not fuel selection. The video explains that hormonal signals — such as insulin and glucagon — direct the switch between macronutrient fuels.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hormonal signals</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Insulin promotes glucose utilisation in the fed state, while glucagon and cortisol shift the body toward fat and protein catabolism during fasting and starvation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Core body temperature</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Thermoregulation is a separate homeostatic mechanism. The switch between carbohydrate, lipid, and protein fuels is governed by hormonal signals, not temperature.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Blood oxygen concentration</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Oxygen levels determine whether metabolism is aerobic or anaerobic, but the overall switch between macronutrient fuel sources is hormonally controlled.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The video states that the body switches between fuel sources based on hormonal signals. Insulin promotes glucose use; glucagon and cortisol mobilise fats and amino acids during fasting."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Hormones like insulin (fed state) and glucagon (fasting state) are the master switches that integrate carbohydrate, lipid, and protein metabolism across organs."
                }
              ],
