          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>According to Peter Mitchell's chemiosmotic hypothesis, the energy used to synthesise ATP is stored as:</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>A high-energy chemical intermediate</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This was the prevailing theory before Mitchell. He demonstrated that energy is stored as an electrochemical proton gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane, not as a chemical intermediate.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>A covalent bond between ADP and inorganic phosphate</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The phosphoanhydride bond in ATP is the product of the process, not the energy store that drives it. The proton-motive force across the membrane powers the formation of this bond.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>An electrochemical proton gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Complexes I, III, and IV of the electron transport chain pump protons across the inner mitochondrial membrane, and ATP synthase then uses that gradient to manufacture ATP — Mitchell's Nobel Prize-winning insight.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>A conformational change in cytochrome c</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Cytochrome c is a mobile electron carrier between Complexes III and IV. The energy store itself is the proton gradient across the membrane, not a structural change in any single protein.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Mitchell proposed that Complexes I, III, and IV pump protons across the inner mitochondrial membrane, creating an electrochemical gradient. ATP synthase then uses this gradient to synthesise ATP."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Mitchell's chemiosmotic hypothesis — that a proton gradient, not a chemical intermediate, drives ATP synthesis — is considered one of the most elegant ideas in biochemistry and earned him the 1978 Nobel Prize."
                }
              ],
